---
import PageLayout from '@/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
---
<PageLayout title="Overview">
  <div class="prose-bfs">
    <h2>Our Philosophy</h2>
    <p>
      A 2009 feasibility study into the outcomes of autistic adults with high IQs (those who had received conventional education) found that only 12% were employed full or part-time, and only 3% could live independently. This underlined the need for a fundamentally different approach to autism education.
    </p>
    <p>
      At Bright Futures, our core philosophy is that children with autism can flourish when the environment, communication style, and educational approach are genuinely adapted to meet their needs — not when children are expected to adapt to a neurotypical school environment.
    </p>

    <h2>Our Practice</h2>
    <p>
      Our guiding methodology is Relationship Development Intervention (R.D.I.) — a developmental approach to autism that focuses on building the core foundations of dynamic intelligence: flexible thinking, joint attention, co-regulation, and experience-sharing.
    </p>
    <p>
      Staff receive Level 1 'guiding' training and provide 45 minutes of guided input on four days per week, in addition to 1-1 academic learning.
    </p>

    <h3>Our Core Offer</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>A low-stimulus, purpose-built environment</li>
      <li>Individual 1-1 classroom spaces for every pupil</li>
      <li>Learning Mentors trained in R.D.I. / guiding</li>
      <li>Qualified teaching staff oversight</li>
      <li>Reduced demands and anxiety-aware communication</li>
      <li>Social communication development over 'social skills' training</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>School Hours</h2>
    <p>
      Mon / Tue / Thu / Fri: <strong>9.15am – 2.15pm</strong><br />
      Wednesday: <strong>10.00am – 3.00pm</strong>
    </p>

    <h2>Assessment</h2>
    <p>
      Pupil progress is assessed continuously by Learning Mentors and reviewed by teaching staff. We use a range of tools to track academic, social, and developmental progress.
    </p>

    <h2>Key Stage 4 Provision</h2>
    <p>
      At Key Stage 4, pupils work toward Functional Skills assessments and ASDAN coursework, building both academic credentials and practical life skills in preparation for adulthood.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
